<subsection xml:id="subsec-volume-of-regular-polygons">
    <title>Volume of Solids.</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
          Definitions:   
        </p>
        <p>
        Volume is the geometric space occupied by an object, or the contents of an object. It is measured in
       cubic units.
    </p>
    <p>
        Computation of a volume is achieved by multiplying the area of the base of the solid
        by the height of the solid
    </p>
    <p>
        Let us proove this from the following examples.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
               Find the volume of the following cube whose side is <m>5cm.</m> 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
               Step 1: Find the area of the base
               <md>
                <mrow> \text{Area of square} =  \amp S^2</mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 5^2</mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 25 cm^2</mrow>
               </md>
            </p>
            <p>
               Step 2: Multiply the area of the base by the height of the solid to find the volume 
               <md>
                <mrow> \text{volume} = \amp \text {areaof base} \times \times{height}</mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 25 cm^2 \times 5 </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 125 cm^3 </mrow>
               </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The volume of the cube is 125 <m>cm^3</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Finding the volume of a triangular prism.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
               Step 1: Find the area of the base
               <md>
                <mrow> \textbf{area of triangle =}\amp \frac{1}{2}b \times h</mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 9cm \times 12 cm </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 54 cm^2 </mrow>
               </md> 
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 2: Multiply the area of the base by the height of the solid to find the volume
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Volume} = \amp \text{area base} \times height</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{2}b \times h \times H</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 54 cm^2\times 25cm </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 1350 cm^3 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
              The volume of the triangular prism is <m>1350 cm^3</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
              Find the volume of the following cylinder using <m>\pi = 3.142</m>. Leave your answer  (correct to 2 decimal place): 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Step 1: Find the area of the base
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text {area of circle } = \amp \pi r^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \pi(8)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \pi 64cm^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 3,142  \times 64cm^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 201.088 cm^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
              Step 2: Multiply the area of the base by the height of the solid to find the volume  
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                   <mrow> \text{Volume} = \amp \text{area base} \times height</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \pi r^2 \times h  </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp201.088 cm^3 \times 20 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 4021.76 cm^3 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
               The volume of the cylinder is <m>4021.76 cm^3 </m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    </introduction>
